Amaron|Ameron	One of Emperor Kellanved’s companions who vanished after Laseen’s takeover of the Malazan throne; his body was never found. Bult suggested the companions deliberately abandoned Laseen after Kellanved and Dancer’s murder. He was described as a large Napan man with a deep-blue Napan face and later “rather wide around the middle,” and Admiral Nok said he was half-Napan.
Apt	Nine-foot-tall Aptorian demon native to Shadow and aligned with High House Shadow, once the fallen concubine of a Demon Lord. Distinctive appearance with one clawed foreleg extending from a split chest, two thin hindlegs, flat elongated head with long snout and slitted nostrils, and a predominantly black body with dun-grey torso covered in thick, spiny bristles. Possesses one slate-grey, multi-faceted eye observing with appalling awareness. Communicates through rapid, rasping clicks and hisses, and demonstrates remarkable speed and endurance while neither eating nor drinking. Initially serves as Shadowthrone's spy monitoring the Whirlwind convergence, but after witnessing Kalam's compassion toward crucified victims, spirits over a thousand children away from execution. Assigned as Kalam Mekhar's guardian by Sha'ik, developing a protective bond that sees her repeatedly save his life throughout Deadhouse Gates. Adopts the severely disfigured boy Panek, requesting Shadowthrone reshape his face to resemble hers with one central eye. Dies heroically at the First Throne defending against Tiste Edur forces when Icarium cuts through her neck with his sword during their fatal confrontation.
Aragan	Staff Sergeant in the Malazan Empire, described as tall and battle-scarred; he seemed to suffer regular headaches.
Aralt Arpat	Member of the Red Blades in Ehrlitan under Tene Baralta; described as a huge, tall man.
Aren City Treasurer|Aren treasurer	A noble who served High Fist Pormqual in Aren; tall and stooped with a thin hatchet face, long pallid fingers, and a high-pitched voice, with light-blue powdered cheeks and painted eyebrows. He wore oversized Napan sea gear with a sealskin hood.
Baria Setral|Baria	Commander of the Red Blades military unit stationed in Dosin Pali. He came from a family of soldiers—his brother Mesker served alongside him, while another brother, Orto, commanded Red Blades forces in the city of Aren. He wore chain armour interwoven with Otataral links as proof against sorcery, along with matching chain leggings and a helmet featuring a slitted visor. His personal grooming included an oiled beard, contributing to his commanding presence as a seasoned military officer.
Baudin the Younger	Companion to Felisin Paran and Heboric after the Cull; described as huge and bestial, with small narrow-set eyes and a thuglike appearance, he shows surprising knowledge of the Malazan Empire.
Baudin the Elder	Highly skilled Talon assassin and father of the younger Baudin, also a Talon. He had been in Malaz City on the night of the Shadow Moon and was said to have witnessed events leading to Kellanved and Dancer’s ascension.
Beneth	Korelri slave in the Otataral mining camp of Skullcup, a large astonishingly handsome man with high cheekbones, long curly black hair groomed with whale oil, thick scarred wrists, clean nails, and deep set eyes. He rose to a crime lord role in the camp and gained the trust of Commandant Sawark.
Bent	Tawny-haired Wickan cattle-dog who took part in the Chain of Dogs; his name came from a hoof-blow that left his head’s bones healed lopsided, giving him a manic half-snarl and a vicious gleam in his eyes. He was often found in the company of Roach.
Berkru	Merchant from Ehrlitan with Durhang-stained teeth; his wiry, sunken-eyed wife painted her face in a style best left to young maidens and peddled fraudulent Deck of Dragons readings to earn extra money.
Bidithal	High Mage of the Raraku Apocalypse and eldest of the three High Mages in the Army of the Whirlwind; described as ancient and withered with filmy eyes, he was known for stealing young girls and forcibly circumcising them, and mistakenly thought himself subtle.
Binadas Sengar	Tiste Edur mage of House Sengar, third son of Uruth and Tomad; brother to Fear, Trull, and Rhulad, and of the four he was the most remote, evasive, and difficult to predict.
Blistig	Malazan Commander of the Aren Guard, a burly armed bearded man who wore a torc on his left arm to denote rank. He had a blunt wide face with solid broad features and scarred cheeks, and was known by a mocking nickname used out of his earshot.
Bordu	Leader of a group of bandits in the Orbala Odhan who claimed to be fighting for the Uprising. Demonstrated opportunistic and coercive behavior, manipulating travelers into joining his gang for raids. His character represents opportunistic elements within larger movements, willing to use pressure and deception to achieve his goals regardless of stated ideological commitments.
Brokeface	Former soldier and follower of Poliel in G'danisban, bone-scarred with a pinched, misshapen face; the flesh and bones folded across his jaw and cheekbone, his eyes were misaligned in sunken sockets, and his mouth was a collapsed cave.
Bula	Innkeeper at Skullcup, a Malazan otataral mining camp on Otataral Island; Bula's Inn stood near the marketplace on Rathole Round, close to Sawark's Keep.
Bult	An experienced Wickan warrior serving as second-in-command to Fist Coltaine during the Malazan campaign in Seven Cities. Though Coltaine occasionally referred to him as "uncle," the actual family connection remained ambiguous. A distinctive scar running from the right jawline to the left brow gave his wide face a folded appearance, while his gnarled legs and jagged teeth added to his weathered appearance. Despite his worn features, he maintained a sharp sense of humor, often joking and laughing with his commander and fellow staff.
Bungle	Originally the sergeant of the sappers in Coltaine’s 7th Army under Captain Mincer; after the Vathar disaster she was promoted to captain and maintained the tradition of not attending command meetings.
Chenned	Captain in Coltaine's 7th Army and likely a veteran of the Wickan Wars; Lull said his father was rumored to have served in Dassem Ultor's First Sword.
Clam	Undead servant of the merchant Nawahl Ebur; a pale man in rags whose lips were gnawed off into a permanent grin, who remembered he had once been named Iryn Thalar, and argued with the other undead over whose death was worst.
Coltaine	Leader of the Wickan Crow clan, about forty years old, with a lean lined face, thin wide mouth, and dark deep set eyes marked by squint tracks. He wore oiled braids knotted with crow feather fetishes, a battered chain vest over a hide shirt, and a crow feather cloak, and became the first Wickan Fist after pledging loyalty to the Malazan Empire.
Cuttle	Veteran sapper in the Malaz 7th Army, described as a burlier, more miserable version of Hedge; squat and blunt-featured with a scarred, pitted face, he wore a leather cap and a random collection of boiled-leather fittings over a threadbare, faded-magenta uniform.
Duiker	Imperial Historian attached to the Malaz 7th Army, born on the plains of Dal Hon, with dark skin and fluent Dosii that served him well in Seven Cities. A veteran soldier skilled with sword and crossbow, he wore local dress including a cowled Telaba cloak while on campaign.
Febryl	High Mage and elder advisor to Sha'ik, called the most craven and conniving of the Whirlwind’s three High Mages; he had tiny black glittering eyes, gold-capped upper canines said to hold the poison Emulor, and wore an oversized silk Telaba whose hood made him resemble a desert snake.
Felisin Paran|Felisin	Youngest Paran sister of house Paran, sister of Ganoes and Tavore, often described as too soft for this world.
Felisin Younger	An orphan of about eleven or twelve who lived in Raraku; because no one spoke for her in the naming rites she had no name. She rarely spoke, but when she did it was with the words of a poet, and she was skilled at braiding flowers.
Fisher kel Tath|Fisher	Poet and bard whose works were well known and often used as chapter epigraphs; his most famous work was the epic Anomandaris, and he was a genius with the lyre and many other instruments, knowing songs from a hundred cultures on dozens of worlds. The “Kel” in his name was spelled with both upper- and lower-case K.
Gall	Warleader of the Khundryl Burned Tears, a huge man with black tear-tattoos gouged down his broad cheeks and sharp gray eyes; he wore grayish hide armor beneath skins and furs and carried tulwars.
Geburah	Member of the Hissar City Guard; he wore a chain vest under a red telaban and a peaked bronze helmet, and carried a pike and a tulwar.
Gothos	A Jaghut and author of Gothos' Folly and A Life in Mists; over seven feet tall and gaunt with greenish skin, long gray hair tied back, huge tusks curling from his lower jaw, and eyes the color of dirty ice.
Gryllen	A D'ivers known as the Tide of Madness, capable of transforming into a swarm of thousands of rats. He had terrorized the city of Y'Ghatan until Malazans drove him out using fire. Travelling as a wealthy merchant called Nawahl Ebur in a palanquin carried by undead servants, he pursued ascendancy through the Path of Hands in the Raraku desert.
Gunnip	Dosii captain stationed at Skullcup, a Malazan otataral mining camp on Otataral Island. Known for his cruel treatment of prisoners under his command, he proved willing to turn against his own Malazan allies during the Whirlwind rebellion.
Hanor	Soldier of the Whirlwind in the Orbala Odhan on Seven Cities; he wore a set of boiled leather armor and led a small band during the uprising.
Heboric Light Touch|Heboric	Former High Priest of Fener and an exiled historian, originally a cutpurse from Malaz City's Mouse Quarter who earned his surname "Light Touch" from his skill at theft before becoming a scholar and priest. His historical writings criticizing fellow historian Duiker and investigating dangerous political truths about Empress Laseen led to his downfall and exile to the Otataral mines. He was described as resembling a sunken-eyed toad, with his body covered in full-body tattooing depicting Fener as a rampaging boar—minute, black, square-etched symbols hidden within an overall pattern covering skin like a wrinkled scroll. Most notably, he had no hands—a ritual punishment inflicted during his excommunication.
Hentos Ilm	T'lan Imass Bonecaster of the Logros clan who pursued the Unbound; smaller than the others, she wore oily, ragged feathers from colourful birds, had long silver hair streaked with red, wore shell, antler, and bone jewelry, and carried no weapons.
Icarium	Mixed blood Jaghut, a Jhag wanderer who suffers constant amnesia and a fractured mind that recalls fragments of ancient events while forgetting recent days. Known by many names such as Lifestealer and Maker of Time, he travels with his companion Mappo Runt and is famed across the world.
Ilem Trauth	Historian known for Lives of the Conquered, a book describing cultures subjugated by the Malazan Empire and reflecting on imperial occupation.
Iskaral Pust|Iskaral|Pust	Old Dal Honese High Priest of Shadow and Magus of High House Shadow who lived in Tesem, an abandoned monastery in Seven Cities. He claimed to be Shadowthrone’s chosen mortal and master of Rashan, Meanas, and Thyr, and was a scrawny tattooed man with a hawk nose, wiry beard, and skin like dark honey.
Jelem	Soldier of the Whirlwind in the Orbala Odhan on Seven Cities; wore boiled leather armour and served among the uprising's local forces.
Karpolan Dem|Karpolan Demesand	Native of the small fortress city of Trygalle in southern Genabackis; a founder of the Trygalle Trade Guild, a caravan master, High Mage, and merchant, described as huge with gold-capped, diamond-studded teeth, pudgy hands, a round face, and small bright eyes, often dressed in silks and prone to profuse sweating.
Kamist Reloe|Kamist|Reloe	High Mage in the Army of the Apocalypse, described as gaunt to the point of skeletal, with grey hair cut to a stubble, a tightly curled iron beard, prominent cheekbones, and sunken eyes. A senior mage figure in the rebellion with a severe and ascetic appearance.
Keneb	Captain in the Orbal garrison on Seven Cities, husband of Selv and father of Kesen and Vaneb, with Minala as his sister in law. An officer of the Malazan Empire whose household ties and garrison role defined his place in the early Seven Cities crisis.
Kimloc	A Tanno Spiritwalker residing in Ehrlitan, distinguished by his role as a spiritual guide and healer within Seven Cities. An elderly man with amber eyes, dressed in an orange robe, whose physical presence conveyed both wisdom and otherworldly connection. His residence was a hidden dwelling within a merchant neighborhood featuring distinctive glass walls and linen-draped doorways. The household bustled with activity, including his granddaughters, medical staff, and military personnel, suggesting his importance as both a family patriarch and community figure. His laughter reportedly sounded like blowing sand, emphasizing his spiritual essence and connection to the desert environment.
Korbolo Dom|Dom	Half Napan Fist in the Malazan Army stationed in Halaf, blue skinned with pudgy hands and thick lips, shaved hairless with dusty blue skin latticed by scars and an expression of cool disdain. A hard edged Malazan officer known for his contempt of gods and magic.
Kulp	Cadre mage in the Malaz 7th Army whose warren is Meanas. Described as squat with a narrow face, white hair, wiry eyebrows, and a sunburned look. A professional soldier mage who serves as a trusted specialist amid the army ranks.
Lady Gaesen|Gaesen	Noblewoman living in Unta and wife of Lord Hilrac, described as a gaunt old woman with a haughty imperious manner.
Leoman of the Flails|Leoman	Captain in the Raraku Apocalypse and bodyguard of Sha'ik. Lean and dark skinned with startling light blue eyes, he carried two one handed morning stars and a crossbow, and wore a colorless Telaba scarf over a peaked iron helm.
Lenestro	Kanese noble residing in Sialk, Seven Cities, holding a prominent mercantile position as Factor in the largest trade enterprise exporting the finest tanned camel hide and titled First Potency within the Guild. A diminutive, rotund man burdened by an oversized gold-brocaded cloak that appeared out of proportion to his small frame. Exhibited self-centered and petty characteristics, often expressing concern primarily for his own comfort and that of his servants. Owned Roach, a rare lapdog from Li Heng maintained on a jewel-studded leash. Survived the Chain of Dogs march with Coltaine as one of approximately one thousand nobles among the refugees, serving on the Council of Nobles and regularly demanding preferential treatment from military leadership. Reached Aren safely after the march but was later killed in Aren by sapper Cuttle, resulting in Cuttle's imprisonment.
List	Young recruit and corporal in Fifth Company of the Malaz 7th Army in Hissar who served under Fist Coltaine. Trained for urban combat and escort missions, he was noted for dying in every mock engagement, which left him lingering near the command tent and listening to strategy sessions.
Lord Hilrac|Hilrac	Nobleman living in Unta and husband of Lady Gaesen, described as a regal older man with a shaved scalp and short grey beard.
Lull	Falari captain in the Sialk Marines, part of Cartheron Wing within the Sahul Fleet, who became one of Fist Coltaine's most dependable officers during the Chain of Dogs campaign. A blue-eyed man with characteristic fiery red long beard and wavy hair bearing distinctive features of his seafaring heritage. Developed a close friendship with Imperial Historian Duiker, who affectionately called him "old man," and was instrumental in bringing soldiers like Gesler, Stormy, and Truth into the marine ranks.
Lostara Yil|Lostara|Yil	Pardu woman from Ehrlitan and officer in the Red Blades, holding the rank of captain and serving under Tene Baralta. She was described as dark skinned with Pardu tattoos, large black eyes set wide above high cheekbones, and a narrow aquiline nose.
Mallick Rel|Mallick|Rel	Chief advisor to High Fist Pormqual on Seven Cities and a Falari Jhistal priest of Mael with access to the Warren of Ruse. Described as fat with soft hands, full lips, heavy lidded eyes, and skin the color of oiled leather, with short colorless hair, green stained teeth, and ocean blue robes adorned with rings.
Mappo Runt|Mappo|Runt	Full blooded Trell and companion to Icarium, big even for his people with broad shoulders, sinewy long arms, and a mane of black hair braided and studded with fetishes. He had deep warm brown skin, sand colored eyes in a robust face, massive sharp canines, and could see in the dark.
Mebra	A Seven Cities spy in Ehrlitan, who secretly hated the Malazan occupation of his home continent. He exemplified deception and untrustworthiness, representing an intelligence operative willing to betray anyone for strategic advantage. He maintained connections with the Bridgeburners dating back to the initial Malazan conquest, with Kalam Mekhar claiming he owed him a personal debt from that era. Physically, he was a small man with sharp silver-capped teeth who carried a dagger at his belt, presenting an appearance befitting his shadowy profession as a spy and manipulator operating within occupied territory.
Megara	Bodyguard to the Aren treasurer.
Mesker Setral|Mesker|Setral	A Red Blade commander, brother of Baria Setral, associated with Dosin Pali. He arrives in Hissar via an unscheduled boat along with his brother and their Red Blade units, announcing their intention to begin their stay with violence against Wickans and traitors when confronting Wickan warriors at the harbour market. However, he and Baria are forced to back down when the Hissar Guard and Wickan bowmen arrive.
Messremb	A Soletaken capable of shapeshifting between human and animal forms. His animal form is a great brown bear as huge as a noble-born's carriage. In his human guise, he presents quite differently: an emaciated figure no taller than five feet, nearly hairless with a narrow face, prominent teeth, and small garnet eyes set within laugh lines. He shares a long history with Mappo Runt, having known him long ago when both lived in the pine forests of the Trell north of Nemil, suggesting he is an old, powerful being with deep roots in the world's mythology and geography.
Minala	Wife of Colonel Tras, commander of the Malazan garrison at Orbal on Seven Cities, originally from Quon. Sister of Selv, whose husband Keneb served at Orbal. Described as attractive and medium boned with iron streaked hair and startling grey eyes, and known as an exceptionally skilled rider who endured an abusive marriage.
Moby	Bhok'arala living in Mammot's study eating grapes and drinking out of the scholar's inkwells. Following his master's death, the creature demonstrated unusual loyalty by accompanying Crokus, Fiddler, and Kalam on their journey through Seven Cities, with his attachment to Fiddler in particular hinting at an intelligence and emotional capacity beyond typical familiars.
Nawahl Ebur|Nawahl|Ebur	Wealthy-merchant persona used by the D'ivers Gryllen, traveling by palanquin carried by four undead servants in Raraku; hosted Heboric, Felisin, and Kulp.
Nether	Wickan warlock or witch and twin sister to Nil, affiliated with the Malaz 7th Army. Dark skin and eyes like black liquid, hair cut bristly short, and a high piping voice. One of the reborn Wickan warlocks, she carried knowledge and strength beyond her years while serving in Sormo Enath cadre as a child.
Nethpara	Malazan noble residing on Seven Cities during the Whirlwind rebellion. Despite potentially being muscular in his youth, had become fat with age, wearing a light-blue brocaded cloak and maintaining a fastidious appearance even during hardship, eventually becoming like a wrinkled leather bag from deprivation. Member of the noble refugee group escorted by Fist Coltaine's 7th Army, serving on the ad hoc Council of Nobles during the Chain of Dogs march. Allied with fellow noble Pullyk Alar, conspiring with other nobles to betray Coltaine's leadership. At the Vathar River crossing, he and his allies made a secret pact with enemy commander Korbolo Dom, initiating an unauthorized refugee crossing that led to a catastrophic ambush killing approximately 20,000 people. Imperial Historian Duiker strangled him after learning of his betrayal, and when they reached Aren, kicked Nethpara in the throat during his attempt to discredit Coltaine and Duiker to High Fist Pormqual, crushing his windpipe fatally.
Nil	Wickan warlock and twin brother of Nether, affiliated with the Malaz 7th Army. Long unkempt black hair and a reedy voice, he sometimes carried a feather bedecked knobbed club. He served in Sormo Enath cadre as a boy and traveled to Hissar to support Coltaine.
Nok	Admiral and Supreme Commander of the Imperial Malaz Navy, commanding from his flagship the Star of Unta. He was one of the last surviving members of Emperor Kellanved's original inner circle, distinguished as "the only admiral who didn't drown" among that legendary cadre. Renowned for his taciturn nature and cold demeanor earning him the epithet "cold iron," he presented as a quite old but well preserved man with weathered features, sporting distinctive white hair, thin snowy brows, and a white moustache and goatee, with a tall thin frame reflecting decades of service at sea.
Pearl	Mockra mage and Claw agent, tall and handsome with dark skin and a lean sharp featured face, green eyes, green silks, and rings of green hued gems. One quarter Tiste Andii. He wore a belt of throwing stars and a brace of throwing knives under his half cloak, and had once been Topper favored lieutenant.
Pella	Malazan soldier garrisoned at the Otataral mining camp Skullcup. A young man called the boy, with calluses ridging the index finger and thumb of his sword hand. He guarded Nearlight Gate and quoted Kellanved from Duiker Imperial Campaigns while on duty.
Pullyk Alar|Pullyk|Alar	Young Malazan noble from Quon Tali living in Seven Cities with honey-coloured skin and large eyes marking him as a native of Quon Tali. An accomplished swordsman who carried a basket-hilted rapier at his side, described as lean with the physical assurance of a duellist. According to historian Duiker's observations, possessed "something in the man's eyes that suggested here was someone who enjoyed killing," using his martial skills and noble status to intimidate those he deemed beneath him with veiled threats of violence. During the Whirlwind Uprising, joined the refugee column led by Fist Coltaine and became part of the ad hoc Council of Nobles, where he advocated for accepting enemy commander Korbolo Dom's offer of safe passage alongside fellow conspirator Nethpara.
Rellock	Father of Sorry, a fisherman in a coastal village on Itko Kan's shores where he and his daughter lived in a modest hut near the tidewater. A wide-shouldered bow-legged man with brown eyes, muscular, hairy, and deeply tanned physique. Lost an arm during the siege of Li Heng when Imperial forces retook the city, burning off his limb during combat. Operated as a fisherman whose catch was sold at Gerrom's market. Faced financial hardship when gods Cotillion and Ammanas possessed his daughter, leaving him indebted to lender Ilgrand. Was spared death through divine intervention, later receiving a mysteriously restored arm while serving in a Shadow temple.
Ryllandaras	Soletaken and D'ivers known as the White Jackal, White Jackal of Winter, and Quon Curse. In man jackal form he is towering and powerful with sandy yellow fur fading to creamy white at throat and chest, dark streaks along the back, long limbs and amber claws, a long black muzzle, and dark carmine eyes.
Salk Elan	Pseudonym used by Pearl of the Claw while traveling with Kalam on the Ragstopper to Unta.
Sawark	Captain and Malazan commander of the guard in the Otataral mining camp Skullcup, presiding from a hexagonal tower keep. Pale, thin, and wiry, with twisted cable like forearm muscles, an oiled beard, short black hair, watery green eyes, high cheekbones, and a wide mouth that rarely smiled.
Sha'ik	The title for the chosen one of the Whirlwind Goddess, also known as the "Hand of Dryjhna" and "Seeress of the Apocalypse." The original Sha'ik was a prophetess and leader of the Whirlwind rebellion in the Holy Desert Raraku. She was a small, dark-haired woman whose appearance reflected her harsh desert life.
Sormo E'nath|Sormo|E'nath	Reincarnation of the greatest Wickan warlock of the same name, reborn after his death at Unta and said to be about ten years old when he led Coltaine warlocks. Tall bow legged boy with dark eyes, a goat head cowl, and a reedy voice, bearing the aura and scent of an ancient warlock who had reached the Time of Iron.
Sulmar	Nobleborn captain in Coltaine's 7th Army during the Whirlwind rebellion who became part of the Chain of Dogs and functioned as the mouthpiece for the nobles in the train of refugees. Characterized as dark-skinned and short, with a greased mustache, possessing both Kanese and Dal Honese ancestry. Had a habitually dour expression and shoulders that seemed to slope as if carrying a lifetime of burdens. Following the Battle of Gelor Ridge, advocated that the army divert to the port city of Ubaryd rather than continue toward Aren, believing Admiral Nok could provide resupply or rescue. Coltaine rejected this proposal, leading to conflict with officers like Lull and Coltaine threatening to strip him of rank. Last mentioned before the Battle of Sanimon, likely perishing along the Aren Way or with the remaining 7th Army forces near Aren's gates.
T'amber	Aide and rumored lover of Adjunct Tavore Paran, quiet and not very talkative, described as beautiful and remote with unclear origins, her name tied to a tawny mane or amber colored eyes.
Tavore Paran|Tavore	Second child of house Paran, sister to Ganoes and Felisin.<br><br> <i>"Command does not come from consensus. I deliver the orders and my officers are to obey them. They should be relieved that is the case, for all responsibility lies with me and me alone. No-one else shall have to answer to the empress."</i>
Tene Baralta|Baralta	Commander of the Ehrlitan Red Blades, a military unit native to Seven Cities, who eventually rises to the rank of Fist within the Malazan Empire's 14th Army. Physically, he cuts an imposing figure—described as tall, broad, and dusk-skinned with a distinctive beard kept slick with oil, reflecting his vanity noted by fellow soldiers. Those who serve under him, like Lostara Yil, perceive him as somewhat self-serving: someone willing to take credit for every success while avoiding responsibility for failures, creating tension between his authoritative bearing and questionable judgment.
Tumlit	Malazan noble from Hissar in Seven Cities who served as one of the primary representatives on the Council of Nobles during Coltaine's Chain of Dogs march. An older, bald man whose watery eyes caused him to squint, but who was nevertheless highly observant. Unlike other noble representatives, displayed reasonable judgment and pragmatism, frequently disagreeing with fellow nobles' positions and showing willingness to collaborate with the military for the greater good. Notably inquired about the welfare of conscripted servants and was the only person to notice suspicious activity involving the army's wagons and sappers before the Battle of Sekala Crossing. Brought intelligence about the nobles' separate peace negotiations with Korbolo Dom to Coltaine's attention at Vathar Crossing, demonstrating concern for those beyond his social class. According to other nobles' claims, died from illness around the time of the Battle of Sanimon, though Imperial Historian Duiker harbored doubts about this account.
Toblakai	Escaped slave and fanatically loyal warrior of the Apocalypse in the Holy Desert Raraku, bodyguard to Sha'ik Elder alongside Leoman. A giant over seven feet tall with a wide muscled frame, flat broad face marked by shattered glass tattoos, a single long braid, and a cloak of bhederin hide over shell like armor.
Vered	Cawnese sailor serving in the Malazan Coastal Guard stationed on Seven Cities. Assigned to the Ripath, a patrol vessel based just north of Hissar, where he served with Corporal Gesler. One of many soldiers caught up in the Whirlwind uprising.
